covered: Valid Request: Scenarios cover successful retrieval with default parameters (TC01).
Empty Response: Scenario for no bundles (TC06) and offset beyond total (TC07) cover empty results.
Pagination: Multiple tests cover offset/limit behavior (TC02, TC05, TC07, TC21).
Query Parameters: Tests cover valid/invalid combinations (TC02, TC08, TC09, TC10, TC11, TC14, TC15, TC16).
Authorization: Unauthorized access scenario (TC12) and audit parameter handling (TC03, TC04, TC19, TC20) cover auth/audit behavior.
System/Dependency Failures: System error (TC13) and timeout (TC22) scenarios present.
Security: SQL injection attempt (TC14) and edge-case handling (TC15, TC16).
Performance: Normal load (TC17) and peak load (TC18) scenarios address performance concerns.
Regression: Regression cases for audit MINIMAL with offset 0 (TC19) and backward compatibility (TC20).
gaps: Rate Limiting: No tests verify behavior under rate limiting or throttling scenarios.
Caching Behavior: No tests validate caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or related caching correctness.
Explicit 403 handling: Tests cover 401 unauthorized but do not verify 403 for forbidden access scenarios.
Additional edge-case coverage: While many edge cases are covered, scenarios around extremely large dataset pagination consistency across multiple pages (beyond single page) could be further expanded.
Timeout granularity: Only a single timeout case (TC22); no explicit testing of various timeout durations or retries.
recommendations: Add rate-limiting/throttling tests to ensure the API gracefully handles burst traffic and enforces limits.
Add tests asserting caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) are present and correctly reflect responses.
Add a scenario to cover 403 Forbidden when access is authenticated but not allowed for the resource, if applicable.
Enhance pagination coverage with cross-page consistency checks across multiple successive pages for very large datasets, including boundary transitions.
Include additional timeout/retry scenarios to validate retryable vs non-retryable conditions.
